result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeremy James St. Arnold was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Jeremy James St. Arnold is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Jeremy James St. Arnold was found guilty of Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jeremy James St. Arnold in court with attorney Linda Irene Coleman.  Frederick Ian Bourg appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defense will proceed with the PH today.  Exhibit #1 marked; police report.  Officer Nicholas Suminski sworn and questioned by DA.  DA motion to sequester witnesses; Coleman no obj.; Court grants motion.  Questioning of witness continued by DA.  Witness identifies defendant.  Met woman at address of call; she had blood on lip and face and a big knob on her forehead; she was crying and seemed very upset; while talking with victim, defendant came out of the home telling her not to talk w/ officer.  Witness identifies exhibit #1; officer's police report of incident.  DA offers exhibit #1; no objection from the defense; Court receives exhibit.  Officer listened to the 911 call the next day and copied to CD and forwarded to DA office.  DA requests permission to play 911 recording; recording played.  DA continues questioning of witness; defendant was detained.  Cross by Coleman; do not know who dialed the 911 call;  defendant did have injuries and was bleeding; victim walked toward officer when he got to the home; defendant told victim to get into the house and not talk w/officer; defendant was arrested that night for one count of disorder conduct as domestic and one count of resisting/obstructing;  reviews report, arrested for one count of disorderly conduct; victim went back into the house on her own; did not hear defendant he would hurt victim if she talks w/officer.  Re-direct by DA; victim did tell officer she made the 911 call; she indicated she feared for her life; there were 3 children in the home during the incident; defendant used a demanding voice toward the victim.  Re-cross by Coleman; witness reviews exhibit #1.
Brianna SA sworn and questioned by Coleman; wife to defendant; husband did not threaten her night of incident not to contact law enforcement; spoke with law enforcement night of incident; did not want to talk w/officer any more and wanted to go back inside.  No cross by DA.  No further witnesses.
Argument by DA; moves for bind over.  Argument by Coleman; case has been overcharged; no proof of threat or use of force to prevent contact with police; zero evidence to rise to the felony charges.  DA makes final comments to the Court, implied threat/force was shown, physical abuse implied from the 911 recording.  
Court:  as to count 1 do not find probable cause; as to count 2 do not find probable cause.  
  Jury trial scheduled for April 14, 2016 at 08:30 am.
